<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="623" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[212,1172,1222,1413]" box="[212,333,1222,1246]" pageId="48" pageNumber="623">
<heading box="[212,333,1222,1246]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="48" pageNumber="623" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,333,1222,1246]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="623">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[212,1172,1222,1413]" pageId="48" pageNumber="623">
The specific epithet honours the ‘Karitiana’, the name for an ethnic group of natives, used here as a noun in apposition. The ‘Karitiana’ experienced a brutal demographic decline after contact with the whites. Indeed, the anthropologist Darcy Ribeiro considered them extinct in 1957, however the current population numbers around 320 individuals (
<bibRefCitation author="Storto L &amp; Velden FFV" box="[400,671,1389,1413]" pageId="48" pageNumber="623" pagination="14" refId="ref30750" refString="Storto L, Velden FFV. 2005. Karitiana. Instituto Socioambiental, Povos Indigenas no Brasil [Internet]. [cited 2013 Aug 14]. Available from: http: // pib. socioambiental. org / en / povo / karitiana / print" type="journal article" year="2005">Storto and Velden 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
